itemDescription: Trade unionist and Conservative Party politician (1853-1932)

wikipedia_page.main: Alfred Roger Jephcott JP (14 February 1853 – 14 March 1932) was a British engineer, trade unionist and Conservative Party politician from Birmingham. He sat in the House of Commons from 1918 to 1929.

response: * Alfred Jephcott (1853–1932), English trade unionist and Conservative Member of Parliament for Birmingham Yardley 1918–1929

Gossling was a joiner by trade, and became a member of the executive of the National Federation of Building Trades Operatives and the Amalgamated Society of Woodworkers. In 1924 he was chosen to contest the parliamentary constituency of Birmingham Yardley for the Labour Party. He failed to unseat the sitting Coalition Conservative MP, Alfred Jephcott,  who retained the seat with a majority of nearly 2,000 votes.
